Arguments

.data, x, y

A substrait_compiler()

...

  • select(): see dplyr::select()

    • rename(): see dplyr::rename()

    • filter(): see dplyr::filter()

    • mutate(): see dplyr::mutate()

    • arrange(): see dplyr::arrange()

    • count(): see dplyr::count()

    • distinct(): see dplyr::distinct()

.fn

Function to transform selected .cols; seedplyr::rename_with()

.cols

Columns to rename; seedplyr::rename_with()

.keep

Which columns are retained in output; see dplyr::mutate()

.by_group

sort by grouping variable? seedplyr::arrange()

.add

Use TRUE to add the groupings to the current groupings and FALSE to reset the grouping.

.drop

Not supported, see dplyr::group_by()

.groups

One of "drop_last", "drop", or "keep" (see dplyr::summarise()).

.before

Destination of columns to move; see dplyr::relocate()

.after

Destination of columns to move; see dplyr::relocate()

by

For joins, a join specifier or NULL to use common variables across x and y; see dplyr::inner_join().

suffix

A suffix used to disambiguate columns from x and y if a join would result in duplicate column names.

keep

For joins, use TRUE to keep all output columns; see dplyr::inner_join().

.keep_all

If TRUE, keep all variables in .data; see dplyr::distinct()

wt

Frequency weights; see dplyr::count()

sort

If TRUE, will show the largest groups at the top; see dplyr::count()

name

The name of the new column in the output; see dplyr::count()

Value

A modified substrait_compiler()

Examples

if (FALSE) { # has_duckdb_with_substrait()
library(dplyr)
compiler <- duckdb_substrait_compiler(mtcars)

select(compiler, mpg2 = mpg) %>% collect()
rename(compiler, mpg2 = mpg) %>% collect()
filter(compiler, mpg > 20) %>% collect()
mutate(compiler, mpg + 10) %>% collect()
transmute(compiler, mpg + 10) %>% collect()
arrange(compiler, desc(mpg)) %>% collect()
}
